**APP Mass Calculation:**

Before (just the changed lines):
```typescript
const isComponent = (item: Item): boolean => COMPONENT_TYPES.has(item.type);
// bindings: 1 (item) | invocations: 1 (.has) = 1+2 = 3

const sumItemPremiums = (items: Item[]): number =>
  componentsPremium(items.filter(isComponent)) +
  sumPremiums(items.filter((item) => !isComponent(item)));
// bindings: 2 (items, inline item) = 2
// invocations: 5 (componentsPremium, filter, sumPremiums, filter, isComponent, +) = 6*2 = 12
// Mass: 14
```

After:
```typescript
const isComponent = (item: Item): boolean => COMPONENT_TYPES.has(item.type);
// Mass: 3

const isNonComponent = (item: Item): boolean => !isComponent(item);
// bindings: 1 (item) | invocations: 1 (isComponent) = 1+2 = 3

const sumItemPremiums = (items: Item[]): number =>
  componentsPremium(items.filter(isComponent)) +
  sumPremiums(items.filter(isNonComponent));
// bindings: 1 (items) = 1
// invocations: 5 (componentsPremium, filter, sumPremiums, filter, +) = 10
// Mass: 11
```

**Total mass before: 14 (sumItemPremiums alone)**
**Total mass after: 11 + 3 (new helper) = 14**

The mass is roughly equivalent (the new helper adds 3, but the inline lambda removal saves 3). The win is in Rule 2 (intent): the named predicate `isNonComponent` reveals intent better than an inline arrow with negation, and parallels `isComponent` symmetrically at the call sites.

